    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial and prospectus excerpts, here are the disclosures regarding the AI segment, xAI, Grok, the X platform, and their associated revenues, costs, and capital expenditures:\n\n### 1. AI Segment\n*   **Overview & Strategy:** The AI segment operates a vertically integrated platform spanning gigawatt-scale compute infrastructure, the Grok frontier model, AI solutions, and the X platform. The company is prioritizing growth and investment over immediate profitability, reflecting the segment\'s early-stage development.\n*   **Financial Performance:**\n    *   **2023:** Revenue of $2,961 million; Loss from operations of $(3,973) million (heavily impacted by a $3,775 million impairment charge).\n    *   **2025:** Revenue of $3,201 million; Loss from operations of $(6,355) million; Adjusted EBITDA of $(1,237) million.\n    *   **Q1 2026:** Revenue of $818 million; Loss from operations of $(2,469) million; Adjusted EBITDA of $(609) million.\n*   **Cost Structure:** Cost of revenue includes infrastructure, revenue share, payment processor fees, creator payments, and allocated labor/overhead. R&D expenses are primarily driven by Grok model training, next-gen product development, and data center/cloud computing costs. \n\n### 2. xAI\n*   **Corporate History & Mergers:** SpaceX acquired xAI on February 2, 2026. Prior to this, on March 28, 2025, xAI acquired X Holdings Corp. and X.AI Corp. These transactions were accounted for as common-control reorganizations (due to Elon Musk\'s controlling interest) with retrospective combination of financial statements.\n*   **Strategic Partnerships:** Tesla invested in xAI in January 2026 (later converted to SpaceX equity). This led to collaborative AI projects like "Macrohard" (utilizing next-gen Tesla processors) and "Terafab" (an AI chip manufacturing initiative).\n*   **Debt Repayment:** In a subsequent event, the company repaid outstanding xAI and X term loans and secured notes totaling $18,905 million (including a $1,163 million prepayment penalty).\n\n### 3. Grok\n*   **Model Profile:** Grok is described as a "truth-seeking" frontier Large Language Model (LLM) designed to understand the universe using evidence, logic, and first principles. It achieved frontier-level scientific reasoning (GPQA Diamond score) faster than reported peers. The roadmap includes multi-trillion parameter models (e.g., Grok 5).\n*   **User Metrics & Monetization:** As of March 31, 2026, Grok had approximately 117 million Monthly Active Users (MAUs) using its AI features. It has roughly 1.9 million paid subscribers across "SuperGrok" tiers. \n*   **Enterprise & API:** Offered via Grok Business and Enterprise (license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing) and API access (stand-ready or usage-based).\n*   **Subsequent Events:** On April 19, 2026, the company entered into a compute agreement with Cursor (Anysphere, Inc.) to collaboratively improve Grok and jointly develop new AI models.\n\n### 4. X Platform\n*   **Vision & Metrics:** X is positioned as a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform evolving into an "Everything App" (integrating media, payments, and banking). As of March 31, 2026, it had ~550 million MAUs (out of 1.3 billion supported accounts) generating ~350 million daily posts.\n*   **Monetization & Products:** Monetized via advertising and X Premium/Premium+ subscriptions (~4.4 million paid subscribers). New product launches include "X Money" (financial services, beta launched Nov 2025) and "X Chat" (end-to-end encrypted messaging).\n*   **Risks:** Disclosures warn that user migration, declining engagement, or the presence of offensive content could harm the brand, reduce monetizable usage, and negatively impact the data pipeline used to train Grok.\n\n### 5. Advertising Revenue\n*   **Recognition & Terms:** Recognized when a user engages with an ad satisfying the advertiser\'s criteria. Contracts are typically short-term and cancellable. The company acts as a principal (gross basis) for direct sales and evaluates principal/agent status for Supply Side Platform (SSP) partners.\n*   **Seasonality:** Ad spend is highest in Q4 (end-of-year spending) and lowest in Q1.\n*   **Growth:** 2025 advertising revenue increased by $116 million year-over-year due to increased partner spend on X.\n*   **AI Integration:** Grok is increasingly used to assist advertisers with campaign creation, creative optimization, and alignment with trending topics to make ads feel more like native content.\n\n### 6. AI Solutions Revenue\n*   **Components & Recognition:** \n    *   *Subscriptions (X & Grok):* Recognized ratably over the term (1 month to 1 year).\n    *   *Data Licensing:* Recognized ratably as the customer consumes the data (1 month to 2 years).\n    *   *API Access:* Recognized ratably or as services are consumed.\n*   **Growth:** 2025 AI solutions and infrastructure revenue increased by $465 million year-over-year. This was primarily driven by a $365 million increase in X and Grok subscription revenue and an $88 million increase in data licensing.\n\n### 7. AI Infrastructure Costs\n*   **Components:** Includes data center facilities (leases, hosting, energy, bandwidth, maintenance), server/networking depreciation, public cloud hosting, and related employee compensation.\n*   **Cost Increases:** In 2025, Cost of Revenue increased by $491 million (29.1%), primarily driven by a $412 million surge in infrastructure and cloud computing costs tied to subscriber growth. Q1 2026 R&D expenses also spiked ($1,471 million increase) largely due to GPU hardware depreciation and data center expansion costs.\n*   **Future Commitments:** In March 2026, the company executed an $805 million purchase agreement for additional turbines to power AI infrastructure through 2029.\n\n### 8. AI Capital Expenditures (CapEx)\n*   **Historical vs. Recent Spend:** AI segment CapEx was $463 million in 2023. By Q1 2026, AI CapEx skyrocketed to $7,723 million.\n*   **Strategic Context:** This massive expenditure supports the rapid construction of gigawatt-scale AI compute infrastructure (such as the COLOSSUS II facility in Memphis, Tennessee). The company emphasizes that owning this power-efficient, large-scale infrastructure is a critical strategic differentiator required to achieve and deploy Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) economically.',
