grading compute as successive chip generations arrive).\n*   **Space-Based Routing:** An integrated Starlink network will allow data to be routed dynamically between orbital compute clusters and global end-users, bypassing reliance on terrestrial backhaul infrastructure.\n\n### 3. Space-Based AI Infrastructure\n*   **Next-Generation Satellites:** The company is designing high-performance AI compute satellites specifically built for high-volume manufacturing, low cost, and the reliability required for long-duration operation in the harsh space environment (having already proven survivability against vibration, shock, g-loads, and vacuum exposure with Starlink V1/V2).\n*   **Starship Heavy-Lift Deployment:** Mass deployment of this infrastructure relies entirely on **Starship**. Starship V3 is expected to carry 100 metric tons to orbit, with V4 reaching 200 metric tons. Future generations aim to deliver millions of tons to orbit annually, which is deemed "critical" for deploying AI compute satellites.\n*   **Optical Mesh Network:** As of March 31, 2026, the existing constellation already utilizes over 23,000 inter-satellite lasers to create a dynamic mesh network in space, laying the groundwork for orbital data routing.\n*   **Grok & Lunar Expansion:** This infrastructure is explicitly tied to training and monetizing the company\'s frontier LLM, **Grok**, faster than competitors limited by Earth\'s power grid. Additionally, the company envisions that a future lunar presence could enable "terawatt-scale annual AI compute growth."\n\n### 4. Economics of Orbital Compute\n*   **The "Cost Per Token" Formula:** The company posits that the long-term economics of AI will be won by the company with the lowest "cost per token." This cost is defined as a function of three inputs: the AI model, compute hardware, and energy. The company claims a structural advantage in the latter two.\n*   **Minimal Marginal Energy Costs:** Because the Sun contains 99.8% of the solar system\'s energy, moving power-intensive workloads to orbit reduces the *marginal cost of energy* to minimal levels, entirely bypassing terrestrial physical, environmental, and regulatory power constraints.\n*   **Hardware & Launch Cost Reductions:** \n    *   *Hardware:* Compute costs will be driven down via vertical integration and the development of proprietary custom silicon (leveraging experience from Starlink).\n    *   *Launch:* Starship\'s full reusability is projected to reduce the cost to reach orbit by **99% or more** compared to NASA\'s historical average of $18,500 per kilogram.\n*   **CapEx and Profitability Warnings:** Building this infrastructure requires massive, ongoing capital expenditures. The company warns investors that it may accelerate these investments at any time, which could result in "periods of reduced profitability or increased losses" as it prioritizes long-term orbital dominance over near-term financial performance.',
