egment R&D Expense Breakdown\nR&D expenses are heavily concentrated on the training of "Grok" (the company\'s leading frontier model), the development and testing of next-generation AI-enabled products, and the massive data center compute infrastructure required to support them.\n\n**Core Components:**\n*   **Compute & Infrastructure:** Cloud computing expenses, power generation costs, and equipment lease expenses.\n*   **Hardware Depreciation:** Depreciation of data center assets, specifically processors (GPUs) and networking equipment.\n*   **Personnel & Overhead:** Employee compensation (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation) and allocated overhead costs.\n\n**Recent Financial Drivers & Sub-line Disclosures:**\n*   **2025 Full Year:** AI R&D expenses surged by **$3,888 million** (a 330.8% increase YoY). The sub-line breakdown for this increase includes:\n    *   *GPU Depreciation:* Increased by **$1,673 million**.\n    *   *Infrastructure & Cloud Computing:* Increased by **$1,440 million** (associated with compute infrastructure build-outs).\n    *   *Employee Compensation & Overhead:* Increased by **$775 million**.\n*   **Q1 2026:** AI R&D costs increased by **$1,471 million** YoY, primarily driven by continued depreciation of GPU hardware and cloud/data center infrastructure expenses tied to AI data center expansions.\n*   **Outlook:** R&D expenses are expected to increase in both absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue due to ongoing investments in Grok\'s compute infrastructure and compute agreements (e.g., the compute agreement with Cursor).\n\n---\n\n### 3. AI Segment Operating Expense Detail (SG&A & Restructuring)\nOperating expenses for the AI segment are categorized into Selling, General, and Administrative (SG&A) expenses and Restructuring charges.\n\n#### A. Selling, General, and Administrative (SG&A)\n**Core Components:**\n*   **Employee Compensation:** Salaries, benefits, and share-based compensation for sales, sales support, marketing